<li id="cite_note-77"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-77">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1133582631"><cite id="CITEREFMerrefield2010" class="citation news cs1">Merrefield, Clark (July 30, 2010). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2010/07/30/howard-zinns-fbi-files-reveal-communist-allegations.html">"The Daily Beast"</a>. <q>Zinn, who died in January and was best known for his influential A People's History of the United States, was studying at New York University on the GI Bill when J. Edgar Hoover's FBI opened its first files on him. He was working as vice chairman for the Brooklyn branch of the American Labor Party and living at 926 Lafayette Avenue in what is an area now considered the <a href="/wiki/Bedford%E2%80%93Stuyvesant,_Brooklyn" title="Bedford–Stuyvesant, Brooklyn">Bedford-Stuyvesant</a> neighborhood in Brooklyn.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=The+Daily+Beast&amp;rft.date=2010-07-30&amp;rft.aulast=Merrefield&amp;rft.aufirst=Clark&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.thedailybeast.com%2Farticles%2F2010%2F07%2F30%2Fhoward-zinns-fbi-files-reveal-communist-allegations.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHoward+Zinn" class="Z3988"></span></span>
